- Mixture-of-experts architectures activate only a sparse subset of parameters per token (typically 1-5% of total), achieving the capacity of a dense model at a fraction of the inference cost while maintaining comparable performance on standard benchmarks
- Knowledge distillation from large teacher models (175B+) to smaller student models (7-13B) preserves 85-95% of task performance while reducing inference latency by 10-25x, with the distillation gap widening on tasks requiring multi-step reasoning
- The Chinchilla scaling law (Hoffmann et al., 2022) showed that most large models are significantly undertrained — optimal compute allocation requires roughly 20 tokens per parameter, suggesting a 70B model needs 1.4 trillion training tokens
- Retrieval-augmented generation with learned retrievers (RETRO, Atlas) conditions generation on retrieved passages during both training and inference, enabling smaller models to match larger ones on knowledge-intensive tasks while keeping parameters tractable
- Gradient checkpointing trades 20-30% additional computation time for 60-70% memory reduction during training, enabling fine-tuning of models that would otherwise exceed GPU memory limits at the cost of throughput